"1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1249":"1249","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1279":"1279","about 1215":"about 1215","1332":"1332","1200":"1200","1265":"1265","about 1253":"about 1253","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Grendon, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom":"Grendon, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Grendon, Warwickshire, England":"Grendon, Warwickshire, England","Grendon,Warwickshire,England":"Grendon, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Sapcote, Leicestershire, England":"Sapcote, Leicestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bassett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from Old French <i>basset</i> ‘of low stature’, a diminutive of <i>basse</i> ‘low, short’, either a nickname for a short person or a status name for someone of humble origins.","Altered form of French   Bessette   1 or <b>Besset</b> (see   Bessette   2).","History: William Bassett (<i>c.</i> 1598–1667) came to Plymouth, MA, from Kent, England, in the 1620s; <i>c.</i> 1650 he moved to Duxbury and subesequently to Bridgewater. He had many prominent descendants, among them one of the earliest families on Martha's Vineyard. — The surname <i>Bassett</i> of French origin (see 2 above) is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America."],"variants":[{"name":"Bessette","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Marcel, Armand, Adrien, Normand, Alphonse, Lucien, Cecile, Herve, Jacques, Laurent, Aime.","French: topographic name designating a small wood of birches, from Occitan <i>bès</i> ‘birch tree’ (see   Besse  ), or a habitational name from (La) Bessette, the name of several places in the southern part of France.","Alternatively, an altered form of French <b>Besset</b>: topographic name, a cognate of 1 above. Altered ending reflects the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>."]}]},{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":0,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":9,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":44,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":75,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":100,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":113,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Emma Bassett was born about 1215, in Sapcote, Leicestershire, England as the daughter of William Basset of Sapcote. She had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter with Sir Robert II Grendon - Justice of Assize, Knight. She died in Grendon, Warwickshire, England."},"et":{"about 1215–":"umbes 1215–Surnud","1215–Female":"1215–Surnud","1200–1272":"1200–1272","1235–1279":"1235–1279","1253–Male":"1253–Surnud","1265–Female":"1265–Surnud","1270–1332":"1270–1332","1190–1249":"1190–1249","1190":"1190","1253":"1253","1272":"1272","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1249":"1249","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1279":"1279","about 1215":"umbes 1215","1332":"1332","1200":"1200","1265":"1265","about 1253":"umbes 1253","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Grendon, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom":"Grendon, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Grendon, Warwickshire, England":"Grendon, Warwickshire, England","Grendon,Warwickshire,England":"Grendon, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sapcote, Leicestershire, England":"Sapcote, Leicestershire, England"},"fi":{"about 1215–":"noin 121